In accordance with rule R303, 2468 Team Appreciate and 2687 Team Apprentice would love to share our offseason projects with the public. Each link will take you to a Google Drive file or Github project. CAD files will be in .SLDPRT format, so let me know if you want .STEP files or something else to view.

Every offseason, we assign offseason projects to complete throughout the course of the fall semester to train and create resources for the season. These projects are completely student-led (except for the CAN Distribution Board) and our main focus this year was to teach students about designing and programming for the season. We also focus on training our rookie team, 2689 Team Alpha.

Design/Electrical Projects:

  • CAN Distribution Board v2
    • An updated version of the CAN Distribution Board that includes 5 CAN connections and 3 power connections. Potential use cases would be for a swerve module or gearbox. GitHub - 2468shrm/CAN-Distribution-Board-With-Power-v2: A board to aid with CAN distribution in FRC applications.
  • Capstan Turret
    • A turret that operates on a capstan drive for low backlash and high accuracy. Utilizes nylon 3D prints for sliding. https://drive.google.com/file/d/11SKTNKNbN3HWFLbE87NEgAQ9wJVTDQmD/view?usp=sharing
  • Cascade
    • A short cascade with the intent of testing Delrin brackets as a cheaper alternative to bearings. Able to be rigged as a normal cascade. One thing we found while assembling was that the tubes to construct the frame of the cascade have to be very square. https://drive.google.com/file/d/1u7ZLcpTCmpj5XGW2Q3eDvcrBEnfew3qQ/view?usp=share_link
  • Crate Intake
    • Subsystem to pick up power cubes from the 2018 Power Up game. Arms are made from polycarbonate. The durometer of the compliant wheels on the ends can be changed according to testing. The side arms are restrained by a bungee (not in CAD) from a standoff on the arm to the center standoff of the main bar. https://drive.google.com/file/d/16L1ioIKBT_cCm6NkE-mTiy9KY0LL99Gn/view?usp=sharing
  • Folding Climb
    • This climb mechanism is designed for the 2022 FRC challenge, utilizing two links to traverse across the bars. The first link is controlled by a capstan drive, and the second link, which would bear most of the robot’s weight, is driven by a winch. Unreeling the string attached to the second link moves the arm up due to a gas shock that is situated between the two links. https://drive.google.com/file/d/1RU4gp_gmb2Fkj0NYK3priy677n-A6oD0/view?usp=sharing
  • Gear Turret
    • A simple turret with Delrin bearing stacks to facilitate rotation and a custom machined 10DP gear. https://drive.google.com/file/d/1fCK_agdpPWyeGS73LE12EkDIxv9rM078/view?usp=share_link
  • MAXTube Crush Block
    • Intended for use as an insert in tubes when mounting swerve pods to REV MAXTube to prevent the thin wall from being crushed. https://drive.google.com/file/d/1xoyWAAMf82Cqi1wKSlXYLDQKV8Z3DDCr/view?usp=share_link
  • Radio Mount
    • Case for the Openmesh radio, has openings for ports and signal lights. Suggested filament is PLA. Screw size: 10-32. Designed with heat set inserts for quick access. Heat set inserts: 10-32, installed length: 0.225in, max hole diameter: 0.267 (Mcmaster-Carr 93365A154) https://drive.google.com/file/d/1D0MZZUHm5y351_8ARjfluOT11-NHI6PO/view?usp=sharing
  • RoboRIO Mount
    • Flexible mount for the RoboRIO. Easy to mount with heatset inserts and meant to be reusable. Utilizes ziptie mounting on RoboRIO. Suggested filament is TPU or flexible filament as it can absorb vibration. Screw size: 10-32 https://drive.google.com/file/d/1g1VbQ7j3M_aC6_v404WoQ8Ci8V_10A_y/view?usp=sharing
  • RSL Mount
    • Mount for RSL. Screw size: 10-32. Suggested filament is PLA. https://drive.google.com/file/d/1cMe82t-U4zHeZz8TJT5PL487s4rc8EGR/view?usp=share_link
  • Series Elastic Actuator
    • Allows for elastic deformation while maintaining the position of the motor. Would be useful for mechanisms that are outside of the robot that require additional compliance. Mounts to a planetary gearbox. https://drive.google.com/file/d/1z7B0eZ-V_KFnm7RG8t2Z25aL1CydcnuB/view?usp=sharing
  • Shooter
    • This shooter is designed for the 2022 cargo, and has an adjustable hood design. With three top rollers speed matched to the main flywheel, the design intent was to eliminate spin and provide consistency in shot placement. Furthermore, the dead axle belted hood system was designed to reduce play in hood position as much as possible. https://drive.google.com/file/d/1CD-HMaFDkKv0WF84cVdV6BzGcNDv-bEE/view?usp=sharing
  • Swerve Mule
    • This drivebase was our testbed for refining swerve code. It uses the SDS MK4 modules in combination with the new REV ION structure to create a drivebase. A traditional bellypan was not included to save weight and manufacturing time, and the side holes on the ION stock allow for easy mounting of electronic components. https://drive.google.com/file/d/148HgWA25iuV0OqCV0pBfBZ2wNm-dwjye/view?usp=sharing

More radio mounts: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1cCtaVKPSAA7pCzG4qKm2CFAjAI1aDLXA/view?usp=sharing
https://drive.google.com/file/d/1ZLA9Ce2aZr6ST0c9uMZ3heCM1psh7loj/view?usp=sharing

Programming Projects:

GitHub

frc2468

frc2468 has 19 repositories available. Follow their code on GitHub.

  • Swerve Repository/Template Project:
    • We have made some updates to our original swerve implementation to make it more efficient. This includes rewriting a lot of our VIs to use type definitions and better conventions to make it consistent across our project. We have also added some code for calculating our swerve odometry, and improved on our swerve pod control by eliminating sources of latency. We are currently adding support for a REV implementation: our latest progress can be seen in the REVTemplate branches. We are also improving our path following capabilities: our latest progress can be seen in the Auto branches.
  • Kalman Filter Implementation:
    • This project was an initial attempt to get a Kalman filter up and running. Due to our increased interest this year in localizing our robot, we decided that we wanted to try and write our own. Currently, the implementation is complete, but there are still some minor fixes to be made. This includes better conventions and a better way to integrate various plants, sensors, and uncertainty models. There is an example VI that simulates the Kalman filter in the test folder in our repository.
  • FRC2468-pivision:
    • This year, we tried getting our hands dirty in the realm of coprocessors. Due to the introduction of apriltags this year, we thought it would be cool to write a ROS package for a raspberry pi that could run our vision software for us. So far, we have written some nodes for decomposing the homography matrix from a detected apriltag and visualizing it in matplotlib.
  • Control Methods:
    • This project was an attempt to look at better methods for flywheel control. Last year, we had numerous issues with noisy sensors and imperfect PID tunes. We eventually did find solutions through better rate measurements and implementing i-zones, however we wanted to find a simpler solution. As a result, we went back to basics, looking at bang bang, feedforward, and eventually an interesting take back half implementation from chief delphi. The results are shared in this project.

If you have any questions, please ask! We will do our best to answer them. If you have any comments or feedback, we are always looking to improve, so please post those as well.

EDIT: Added more radio mounts

Hello!

I’m Abhinav, the current programming lead. We use submodules to keep our robot project and swerve library separate, hence the different repositories. However, submodules don’t update when you clone without some additional settings. We’ve always worked around this by running a command to update the submodules afterwards, and I forgot about that when uploading everything publicly. Anyways, to fix your problem, you can run the command below.

git submodule update --init

The other thing with submodules is that switching branches in the higher level repository does not switch branches in the submodules. This means that you need to go into each submodule and update their branch to be compatible with the higher level repository. Since we mirror different branches in our swerve library and swerve template, you will need to change both in order to load the code properly. In our case, these branches are main, Auto, REVTemplate. The swerve submodule folder should be visible in the project root, so just change directories and run a checkout command.

Let me know if this helps. All this info has been added into a README (probably should have done that originally) so that the code is easier to use.
